Test Plan #3 - Hardware-in-the-Loop Integration Test
Introduction
This document outlines the test plan for conducting the GPS Spoofing Detection System Hardware-in-the-Loop (HIL) Integration Test. The HIL test will verify the system’s integration and performance within a simulated aircraft environment, interfacing with emulated GPS, electrical power, and avionics systems under controlled conditions, including simulated GPS spoofing attacks.
Test Objective
The HIL Integration Test will validate that the GPS Spoofing Detection System:

Communicates seamlessly with simulated aircraft GPS systems (User Need 5).
Operates reliably using simulated aircraft electrical power interfaces (User Need 6).
Supports installation compatibility with existing aircraft mounting and power interfaces (User Need 13).
Detects GPS spoofing and activates visual (red light) and audible alerts within 3 seconds (User Needs 8, 9).
Allows user alert cancellation via a button (User Need 10).
Performs Built-in Tests (BIT) every 1 minute, returning results within 10 seconds, with appropriate visual indicators (orange light for BIT failure, red light off) (User Needs 7, 14, 15, 16).
Stores spoofing event data for off-platform transfer (User Needs 3, 4).
Operates without adverse effects on simulated aircraft systems.

Equipment Under Test
The Equipment Under Test (EUT) will consist of the GPS Spoofing Detection System, including:

GPS spoof detection module.
Visual indicators (red and orange lights).
Audible alarm system.
Alert cancellation button.
Data storage unit.
Interfaces for GPS and electrical power systems.

The EUT will be integrated into a Hardware-in-the-Loop test rig simulating an aircraft’s avionics suite, GPS system, and 400 Hz electrical power supply. The HIL environment will include real-time simulation of aircraft systems and GPS signals, with the capability to generate FAA-approved GPS spoofing signals.
Functional Test
The EUT must have passed bench-level functional tests to confirm basic operation and interface compatibility before integration into the HIL test rig.
Acceptance Criteria
The HIL Integration Test will be considered successful if the EUT meets the following criteria:

Maintains continuous communication with the simulated aircraft GPS system without data loss or interruptions.
Operates reliably on the simulated 400 Hz power supply, with no power-related faults or degradation.
Demonstrates compatibility with simulated aircraft mounting and power interfaces, with setup time not exceeding 4 hours.
Detects GPS spoofing signals (Signal-to-Noise Ratio up to TBD) and activates red light and audible alerts within 3 seconds.
Allows user cancellation of alerts, silencing the audible alarm and deactivating the red light.
Performs BIT every 1 minute, completing each test within 10 seconds, activating the orange light and deactivating the red light during BIT failure.
Logs all spoofing events (timestamps, signal characteristics) and supports data extraction post-test.
Exhibits no adverse effects (e.g., faults, mode changes) on simulated aircraft systems, including avionics and GPS.

Test Procedure
The HIL Integration Test will be conducted in a controlled laboratory environment using a HIL test rig, with FAA-approved GPS spoofing signal generation. The test consists of two procedural components: 1) HIL Setup and Interface Verification, and 2) Operational Integration Testing.
HIL Setup and Interface Verification

Setup: Install the EUT into the HIL test rig, connecting it to simulated GPS and 400 Hz power interfaces. Record setup time to ensure it does not exceed 4 hours.
Power Interface Test: Activate the simulated 400 Hz power supply and monitor the EUT for stable operation, checking for voltage stability and absence of power faults.
GPS Interface Test: Establish communication between the EUT and the simulated GPS system. Verify data exchange accuracy and continuity using HIL instrumentation.
Baseline BIT: Execute an initial BIT to confirm EUT integrity before operational testing.

Operational Integration Testing

Spoofing Detection and Alerts: Generate simulated GPS spoofing signals (Signal-to-Noise Ratio up to TBD) via the HIL rig. Monitor the EUT’s response, verifying that the red light and audible alarm activate within 3 seconds.
Alert Cancellation: Trigger a spoofing event and use the alert cancellation button to silence the audible alarm and deactivate the red light. Confirm proper system reset.
BIT Performance: Operate the EUT for at least 10 minutes to allow multiple BIT cycles (every 1 minute). Simulate a system fault to trigger BIT failure, verifying orange light activation and red light deactivation within 10 seconds.
Data Storage and Transfer: Generate multiple spoofing events and verify that data is logged in the EUT’s storage unit. Extract data post-test to confirm accuracy and completeness.
System Interaction: Simulate concurrent operation of aircraft avionics, GPS, and other systems within the HIL environment. Monitor for any interference, faults, or performance degradation in the EUT or simulated systems.

Test Documentation
Detailed test procedures, configurations, and data recording will be documented in the “GPS Spoofing Detection System HIL Integration Test Procedure.” A “GPS Spoofing Detection System HIL Integration Test Report” will be prepared post-test, summarizing results and compliance with acceptance criteria.
Test Instrumentation
The HIL test rig will provide simulated aircraft outputs and displays for monitoring, supplemented by specialized equipment. Table 1 lists the recommended test equipment, with equivalent devices subject to test director approval.



